<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-161-129 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 946 928</DOCID><JOURNAL>CAD-CAM International  May 1991 v10 n5 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Open season. (Advanced Computing Environment and cartels promisingan open standard)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Clarke, Charles.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Cartels that promise open standards have more to do withprotectionism and the promotion of proprietary standards than theydo with openness.andP;  Sun Microsystems was the first to push opensystems and won increased market share with the combination of Sunand AT and T Unix for the workstation commodity product race.andP;  Atthat time in 1987, Apollo systems were actually more connectibleto open environments.andP;  The Open Software Foundation's (IBM, DEC,HP among others) efforts in the open systems market were counteredby Sun with the licensing of the Sparc architecture, which now hasthe better part of the RISC workstation market.andP;  The lateststandards cartel is the Advanced Computing Environment (ACE), agroup of 21 computer and software companies dedicated to thestandardization of software with a unified Unix system based onthe Open Desktop from the Santa Cruz Operation, and compatiblewith OS/2 3.0 from Microsoft.andP;  The future of many microcomputerarchitectures is unknown.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer IndustryStandardizationCompetitionVendorsProprietary SystemsAnalysisMarketing StrategyPromotion of ProductAdvanced Computing EnvironmentConsortiaOpen Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   ACE consortium membership list. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>